        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Sequence-to-Sequence Means"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " describes any task where both the input and output are variable-length sequences. The input and output lengths are independent — a long article can summarise to a single sentence, and a short question can expand into a multi-paragraph answer. This is fundamentally different from classification, where the output is always a fixed label."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The classic neural architecture for seq2seq is the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "encoder-decoder"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": the encoder reads the entire input and compresses it into a representation; the decoder generates the output one token at a time, conditioned on that representation."
          }
        ]
      },
